---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title={`About · ${SITE_TITLE}`}
      description="A site for sharing things built by AI, or built by humans directing AI."
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main class="prose">
      <section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
        <div>
          <h1>This is a site for sharing things built by AI, or built by humans directing AI.</h1>
          <p>
            Some of the work published here is developed mostly by AI agents.
            Some of it is developed by humans who use AI as a tool, a delegate, a pair programmer,
            or an implementation engine. Most of the interesting output lives somewhere in between.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
      <article>
        <p>
          The purpose of this site is simple: to document and share the results of that kind of work.
          Not just the finished artifact, but also the process behind it — what was delegated,
          what was reviewed by a human, what had to be corrected, and what turned out better or worse than expected.
        </p>

        <p>
          "Made with AI" is usually too vague to mean much. It can describe anything from autocomplete,
          to scaffolding, to full agent-driven implementation. This site exists to add detail where that label is too blurry.
          The goal is to make the collaboration visible enough that the result can actually be understood and evaluated.
        </p>

        <h2>What gets published here</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>projects generated or assembled by AI agents</li>
          <li>projects built by a human through AI delegation and supervision</li>
          <li>technical write-ups explaining how those results were produced</li>
          <li>build logs, postmortems, architecture notes, and workflow experiments</li>
          <li>examples where the AI output was useful, flawed, surprising, or worth dissecting</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Why make a site like this?</h2>
        <p>
          Because a lot of AI-assisted development currently vanishes into prompt history,
          chat logs, and private repositories. That makes it hard to study, hard to compare,
          and hard to trust. A public record creates something better: evidence.
        </p>

        <p>
          This site is meant to be that record. A place where outputs can be inspected,
          where methods can be explained, and where the line between human judgment and AI execution
          is treated as part of the story rather than something to hide.
        </p>

        <h2>The underlying idea</h2>
        <p>
          If AI is going to become part of how software gets made, then the resulting work should be publishable,
          reviewable, and discussable in public. That means documenting not only the code or product,
          but the collaboration model that produced it.
        </p>

        <p>
          That is what this site is for: sharing software built by AI, or built by humans who told AI what to build,
          and showing enough of the process that the result is more than just a claim.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
